## Jupyter Notebooks <a id="motd-jupyter-notebooks"></a>

### Get started with Jupyter Notebooks on FAS OnDemand <a id="motd-get-started-with-jupyter-notebooks-on-fas-ondemand"></a>

1. On the menu bar, click `Interactive Apps` and select the Jupyter app for your class. For example, if your class is CS109a, select `Jupyter Notebook - CS109a`.
![Select-jupyter-app screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/select-jupyter-app.png?raw=true)

2. On the following page, in `Allocated Time`, enter the approximate number of hours for which you would like to run your server. For example, for a 4 hour session, enter `04:00:00`. Afterwards, click `Launch`.
![Launch-jupyter-server screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/launch-jupyter-server.png?raw=true)

3. On the page that follows, click `Connect to Jupyter`. A new browser tab containing the Jupyter notebooks interface will open.
![Connect-to-jupyter screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/connect-to-jupyter.png?raw=true)

4. Select the jupyter kernel you want. For example, to start a notebook with the Python 3 jupyter kernel, click `New` then `Python 3`.
![Select-python-3-kernel screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/select-python-3-kernel.png?raw=true)

### How to install python packages in your Jupyter Notebook server <a id="motd-how-to-install-python-packages-in-your-jupyter-notebook-server"></a>

It is probable that the package you need is already pre-installed and that you can import it in your notebooks with `import packagename`. If that is not the case, below are the steps to install a python package.

1. From the jupyter notebooks interface, click `New` then `Terminal`. A terminal will open in a new browser tab.
![Open-a-terminal screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/open-a-terminal.png?raw=true)

2. In the Terminal, run `pip install --user packagename`, replacing `packagename` with the python package you intend to install. E.g:
![Install-python-package screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/install-python-package.png?raw=true)


## Rstudio Server <a id="motd-rstudio-server"></a>

### Get started with Rstudio on FAS OnDemand <a id="motd-get-started-with-rstudio-on-fas-ondemand"></a>

1. On the menu bar, click `Interactive Apps` and select RStudio app for your class. For example, if your class is Gov 50, select `RStudio Server - Gov50`.
![Select-rstudio-App screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/select-rstudio-app.png?raw=true)

2. Click `Launch`.
![Launch-rstudio-server screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/launch-rstudio-server.png?raw=true)

3. On the page that follows, click `Connect to Rstudio Server`.
![Connect-to-rstudio-server screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/connect-to-rstudio-server.png?raw=true)

4. A new browser tab with Rstudio will open. 
![Rstudio-interface screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/rstudio-interface.png?raw=true)

### Troubleshooting Rstudio on FAS OnDemand <a id="motd-troubleshooting-rstudio-on-fas-ondemand"></a>

### Restarting Rstudio <a id="motd-restarting-rstudio"></a>

To restart your Rstudio server completely, follow these steps:

1. Navigate to `My Interactive Sessions` in FAS OnDemand.
![Navigate-to-interactive-sessions.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/navigate-to-interactive-sessions.png?raw=true)

2. Click `Delete` to stop your Rstudio server.
![Stop-rstudio-server.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/stop-rstudio-server.png?raw=true)

3. Click `Confirm` when prompted.  _Note: data that is stored in your home folder will be preserved so when you start a new server, your data will be available._
![confirm-delete-rstudio-session.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/confirm-delete-rstudio-session.png?raw=true)
![after-delete-no-active-rstudio-sessions.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/after-delete-no-active-rstudio-sessions.png?raw=true)

4. Select the Rstudio app and launch a new server.
![Launch-rstudio-server.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/launch-rstudio-server.png?raw=true)

### Error launching Rstudio <a id="motd-error-launching-rstudio"></a>

If you get an error message that looks like this after attempting to launch an application:

![sbatch-error-on-launch.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/sbatch-error-on-launch.png?raw=true)

Wait 1-2 minutes and re-launch the application. This may happen the very first time you login to FAS OnDemand and launch an application (e.g. RStudio Server or Jupyter). 

If you continue to get this error or a similar one after waiting and trying to re-launch your application, then contact ithelp@harvard.edu for assistance.

### Logging back in to Rstudio <a id="motd-logging-back-in-to-rstudio"></a>

If you have been logged out of Rstudio (because of inactivity, for example) then you will see a login screen like this:

![rstudio-login-screen.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/rstudio-login-screen.png?raw=true)

To log back in to your Rstudio session, close that login page and then:

1. Navigate to `My Interactive Sessions` in FAS OnDemand.
![Navigate-to-interactive-sessions.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/navigate-to-interactive-sessions.png?raw=true)

2. Re-connect to your running Rstudio session:
![Connect-to-rstudio-server screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/connect-to-rstudio-server.png?raw=true)

### Working with Rstudio on FAS OnDemand <a id="motd-working-with-rstudio-on-fas-ondemand"></a>

#### How to install R packages in your Rstudio server <a id="motd-how-to-install-r-packages-in-your-rstudio-server"></a>

Rstudio server comes preinstalled with most if not all packages required for your class, so if you can't find the package in the list of installed packages, make sure that you are connecting to the correct Rstudio app for your class before proceeding (e.g. `Rstudio Server - Gov50`).

In the event that you need to install additional R packages, you can install from CRAN or github as follows:
- CRAN: `install.packages('packagename')` 
- Github: `remotes::install_github('user/packagename')`

For example, to install the [shiny](https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/shiny/index.html) package, run `install.packages('shiny')`:

![Install-r-packages.png screenshot](/public/userguide_assets/install-r-packages.png?raw=true)

The packages will be installed to the `R` folder of your home directory. 

